DOCUMENT();

loadMacros('PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'PGstatisticsmacros.pl', 'PGcourse.pl');

Context('Numeric')->flags->set(
    tolerance => 0.005,
    tolType   => 'absolute',
);

$count = random(8, 11);
push(@data, random(50, 70)) for (1 .. $count);

#  Not technically correct but highly likely to made the $mode the mode
$mode = random(50, 70);
push(@data, $mode) for (0 .. 4);
$count += 5;

@data_sorted = num_sort(@data);

$displaysorted = "";
$sum           = 0;
$sum += $_ for (@data);

$mean = $sum / $count;
($min, $q1, $median, $q3, $max) = five_point_summary(@data);

BEGIN_PGML

Your school basketball team posted the following (sorted) scores
in [$count] recent games:

[```[@ join(" ,",   @data_sorted) @] ```]

a) The average game score is [_]{Real($mean)}{10}
b) The median score is [_]{Real($median)}{10}.
c) The modal score is [_]{Real($mode)}{10}.

**Express answers that are not integers to two decimal places.**

END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
a)  The total sum of all of the scores is [$sum].  Therefore the average score is [`` \frac{[$sum]}{[$count]} = [$mean] ``]
b) Since the number of games is [@ $count % 2 == 0 ? 'even' : 'odd' @], the median is the 
[@ $count % 2 == 0 ? 'the average of the middle two values' : 'middle' @] or [$median].
c) The modal score is the score with the most values or [$mode].
END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();
